human_readable.Acute_Goals:
Dear Ms. Thomas de Arroyo,



It was a pleasure taking care of you at Carney Hospital. You were admitted to Carney Hospital and 

received the total left knee replacement without complications. You worked with physical therapy who 

determined that you were safe to go home with PT services.



You are now ready to return home with the following instructions:


- You can bear full weight, as tolerated.


- Please do NOT remove the dressing, and please do NOT get it wet prior to the follow up 

appointment. 


- You may have sponge bath only, do not shower or submerge yourself in water.


- Please call office if dressing becomes saturated prior to the follow up appointment.


- Please call and schedule a follow-up appointment with Dr. McGlowan in 10-14 days. Call the office 

at (781) 618-1944 to schedule your appointment.


- Call the office if you have any questions.



Medications:


- Oxycodone 5 mg, take 1 tablet by mouth every 4-6 hours as needed for pain. Please take fewer 

tablets and space them out to every 6-8 hours as able.


- This is a narcotic pain medication, which often slows the bowels down and you may become 

constipated. It is advisable to take a laxative the first few days after the operation. Please do 

not operate any motorized vehicle while taking the medication.


- Take 1 tablet of Colace 100 mg by mouth twice a day with plenty of water to prevent constipation. 


- Take 1 tablet of Warfarin 2 mg by mouth once a day for 2 weeks. 


- Continue your home medications as prescribed by your regular providers.



Thank you for choosing Carney for your care.



For VNA:


· Please draw blood every Monday (first draw on 6/13/22) and call Dr. McGlowan's Office @ (781) 

618-1944 with results on Tuesdays. 


· Please do NOT touch or change dressing!

Pt reports/exhibits pain at tol level


Including:

- Pain controlled by pharmacological/non-pharmacological means

- Establish realistic pain and function goals prior to initiating opioid therapy 

in patients with chronic pain if applicable 

- Discuss known risks and realistic benefits of opioid therapy

Alteration in Respiratory Status


Patient will maintain airway and adequate gas exchange

Absence of falls


Including:

- Early & often mobilization when appropriate

- Passive/active range of motion as appropriate

- toileting schedule implementation

- implementation of fall risk interventions

Able to achieve maximum mobility level


Including:

- Understands safety

- Demonstrates progress in improved mobility

- Demonstrates correct use of mobility devices if appropriate

- Understands & accepts limitations & plan for progression as appropriate

Surgical site healing


Including:

- Surgical site clean, dry and intact

- Absence of redness or drainage

- Site care continued as applicable

Decrease in sensory misperception


Including: 

- Assess for s/s of Hallucinations and Impaired Sensory Perception

- Reality Orientation

- Diversional Activities

- Promote Family Participation

Discharge instruction:


[] Regular diet as tolerated.


[] If patient has meniscal tear or simple arthroscopy: Weightbearing as tolerated with crutches, and 

begin straight leg raises the day after surgery.  if patient has ACL repair: Partial weightbearing 

as tolerated with crutches. [] Continue to use the splint at all time. Do not remove or change the 

degree of splint.


[] Do not drive or operate machinery for 24 hours.  Someone is to drive you home from the hospital.  

You may walk, do light activity allowed by the use of one arm.  Your return to work will be 

addressed at your first postop visit. Avoid the use of alcohol and sedatives for 24 hours post 

anesthesia.


[] May use ice to the knee 20 to 30 minutes every 4 hours to help reduce the swelling and ease the 

discomfort.  Elevate leg to help reduce swelling to the lower extremity.  


[] Do not remove dressing or get it wet to prevent infection. Keep dressing clean and dry until seen 

by the physician for suture removal.  May sponge bath until appointment.


[] Formal physical therapy orders will be given at his office visit.  


[] Follow-up with Dr. McGlowan in 7 to 10 days after surgery.  Sutures will be removed at this 

visit.


[] Call office at 7816181944 if you have a fever of more than 101 Fahrenheit, numbness or tingling 

of the foot, redness, excessive swelling, draining or bleeding from the wound, increased knee pain, 

calf pain, or questions.


[] Take medication as prescribed.

LEFT  LEG DUPLEX VENOUS ULTRASOUND (93971)


 History:


 LT KNEE PAIN


 Findings:


 Gray scale, color flow, and spectral Doppler evaluation of the  lower extremity

deep veins was performed.


 The common femoral, saphenous femoral junction, superficial femoral and

popliteal veins are patent and compressible.  There is normal respiratory

variation and augmentation.


 The posterior tibial vein to the extent visualized is patent.


 There is no occlusive or nonocclusive thrombus.


 There is a 4 x 4 x 0.8 cm popliteal fluid collection.


 Impression:


 No sonographic evidence of deep venous thrombosis.


 Popliteal cyst.
